53
00:03:13,784 --> 00:03:20,882
Desperate Housewives - Saison 3
Episode no 13 "Come Play With Me"

54
00:03:22,585 --> 00:03:24,951
<i>It can happen so quickly.</i>

55
00:03:25,634 --> 00:03:29,780
<i>In the moment it takes a gunman's bullet
to enter his victim's leg...</i>

56
00:03:30,482 --> 00:03:36,360
<i>in the time it takes to tell a wife her
husband won't be home for dinner...</i>

57
00:03:37,287 --> 00:03:42,348
<i>in the instant it takes a father to meet
his son for the very first time...</i>

58
00:03:45,511 --> 00:03:49,360
<i>yes, life as we know it can change...</i>

59
00:03:50,877 --> 00:03:52,668
<i>in a heartbeat.</i>

60
00:03:53,300 --> 00:03:54,799
Jane's still running a fever.

61
00:03:54,800 --> 00:03:56,399
Yes, and she hasn't responded

62
00:03:56,400 --> 00:03:58,500
to any of the meds that we've tried.

63
00:03:58,900 --> 00:04:00,599
Do you think we should call her husband?

64
00:04:00,600 --> 00:04:02,099
Uh, not just yet.

65
00:04:02,100 --> 00:04:05,000
Let's try vancomycin.
It worked for her before.

66
00:04:05,100 --> 00:04:06,500
I don't want Ian to worry.

67
00:04:07,900 --> 00:04:10,000
This is your new lawyer, Alan Marcus.

68
00:04:10,300 --> 00:04:11,599
Alan, this is Mike Delfino.

69
00:04:11,600 --> 00:04:14,410
Hey, Mike. Sorry I couldn't
start on your case sooner.

70
00:04:14,411 --> 00:04:16,599
I was wrapping up
an armed robbery trial.

71
00:04:16,600 --> 00:04:18,300
It's nice to finally meet you.

72
00:04:19,500 --> 00:04:21,500
And you must be Ian.

73
00:04:21,600 --> 00:04:24,600
I can't thank you enough
for helping me out here.

74
00:04:24,700 --> 00:04:27,000
Susan and I are happy
to be of assistance.

75
00:04:35,100 --> 00:04:36,399
So should we get started?

76
00:04:36,400 --> 00:04:37,200
Sure.

77
00:04:38,838 --> 00:04:39,799
So, Mike,

78
00:04:39,800 --> 00:04:42,299
I've had a chance to review
all the evidence against you,

79
00:04:42,300 --> 00:04:43,799
and I've got a strategy

80
00:04:43,800 --> 00:04:46,200
to ensure your case
never goes to trial.

81
00:04:46,300 --> 00:04:49,100
Don't you love this guy?
What's the strategy?

82
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:52,199
Pleading guilty?
What kind of a strategy is that?

83
00:04:52,200 --> 00:04:53,899
He'd only be pleading
to manslaughter.

84
00:04:53,900 --> 00:04:56,801
- That's still ten years in prison.
- Well, which is better than life,

85
00:04:56,804 --> 00:04:58,995
and that's what Mike's risking
if he goes to trial.

86
00:04:58,996 --> 00:05:00,929
With good behavior,
he could be out in five.

87
00:05:00,930 --> 00:05:03,003
With a better lawyer,
he could be out in zero.

88
00:05:03,683 --> 00:05:06,147
We need to find a lawyer
who believes that he's innocent.

89
00:05:06,148 --> 00:05:08,243
Well, the evidence against him
is very compelling.

90
00:05:08,244 --> 00:05:10,699
You're letting your feelings
for him cloud your judgment.

91
00:05:10,700 --> 00:05:13,899
My "feelings for him"?
Are we gonna do this again?

92
00:05:13,900 --> 00:05:15,999
Do you realize that
every conversation we have

93
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:17,308
winds up being about Mike?

94
00:05:17,309 --> 00:05:19,965
"Who's the best lawyer for Mike?
How can we get Mike acquitted?"

95
00:05:19,966 --> 00:05:22,799
I have told you I love you
a thousand times.

96
00:05:22,800 --> 00:05:25,000
Where is all this jealousy coming from?

97
00:05:27,500 --> 00:05:28,500
Do you know what?

98
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:31,200
I have to catch that plane to Montreal.

99
00:05:31,300 --> 00:05:33,799
What? No, Ian,
we have to talk about this.

100
00:05:33,800 --> 00:05:35,800
I can't be late. It's business.

101
00:05:36,800 --> 00:05:39,800
Look, I have provided Mike
with the best lawyer I know.

102
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:42,491
If you want to get someone else,
then you're on your own.

103
00:05:49,300 --> 00:05:50,306
Whatcha doing?

104
00:05:50,307 --> 00:05:54,600
Oh, deciding what to wear
on my first day back to work.

105
00:05:54,900 --> 00:05:56,500
Do I look fat in this?

106
00:05:57,400 --> 00:05:58,978
I think you look good in everything.

107
00:06:00,100 --> 00:06:02,399
Wow. Your father has taught you well.

108
00:06:02,400 --> 00:06:03,999
What about the street fair?

109
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:06,499
If you're going back to work,
who's gonna take me?

110
00:06:06,500 --> 00:06:08,600
Mrs. Mccluskey. Won't that be fun?

111
00:06:08,700 --> 00:06:09,600
No.

112
00:06:10,900 --> 00:06:12,699
Do you have to go back to work?

113
00:06:12,700 --> 00:06:16,100
Come on. You and your brothers
will be thrilled.

114
00:06:16,600 --> 00:06:18,900
Don't you get tired of me yelling at you

115
00:06:19,500 --> 00:06:22,100
to clean up your room
and finish your homework?

116
00:06:22,900 --> 00:06:24,000
Yeah,

117
00:06:24,300 --> 00:06:26,700
But you've been a lot nicer
since you got shot.

118
00:06:28,900 --> 00:06:30,700
Oh. Well, that's good to know.

119
00:06:31,539 --> 00:06:32,599
When you think about it,

120
00:06:32,600 --> 00:06:35,400
Me going back to work
is not that big a deal.

121
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:38,600
We're only losing all time
together in the afternoon.

122
00:06:38,900 --> 00:06:42,300
But every hour counts.
I miss you all day long.

123
00:06:44,400 --> 00:06:46,499
Oh, honey...

124
00:06:46,500 --> 00:06:47,900
jeez.

125
00:06:51,200 --> 00:06:52,499
Do you really mean that,

126
00:06:52,500 --> 00:06:56,700
or are you manipulating mommy
into feeling incredibly guilty?

127
00:06:57,800 --> 00:06:59,200
A little bit of both.

128
00:07:00,900 --> 00:07:03,400
Yep. Your father's taught you well.

129
00:07:07,900 --> 00:07:09,490
The suspense is killing me.

130
00:07:10,076 --> 00:07:11,099
Here it comes.

131
00:07:11,100 --> 00:07:14,400
And now the moment
we've all been waiting for...

132
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:16,902
the winner of this year's

133
00:07:16,903 --> 00:07:19,100
Little Miss Snowflake pageant is...

134
00:07:19,800 --> 00:07:21,400
Sherri Maltby!

135
00:07:33,200 --> 00:07:36,099
I'm in shock. I mean, I knew
she had a shot at the top five,

136
00:07:36,100 --> 00:07:37,700
But to actually win?

137
00:07:37,701 --> 00:07:39,821
I was sure she'd lose
to that little blonde bitch

138
00:07:39,822 --> 00:07:41,200
who sang that patriotic medley.

139
00:07:41,300 --> 00:07:44,500
I know. She practically had
sparklers coming out of her ass.

140
00:07:45,200 --> 00:07:46,800
Totally shameless.

141
00:07:46,900 --> 00:07:49,399
Okay, hon, let's go
meet those reporters.

142
00:07:49,400 --> 00:07:52,099
- What are y gonna tell 'em?
- I owe it all to "beauty by Vern."

143
00:07:52,100 --> 00:07:53,000
Attagirl.

144
00:07:59,800 --> 00:08:01,899
Oh, Zach.
What are you doing here?

145
00:08:01,900 --> 00:08:03,200
I came to support you.

146
00:08:03,300 --> 00:08:05,899
Oh. Okay, why don't you
support me from the lobby?

147
00:08:05,900 --> 00:08:08,899
I have some networking to do.
My girl just won the pageant.

148
00:08:08,900 --> 00:08:10,700
Oh, yeah, I know, and you're welcome.

149
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:15,000
What did you do?

150
00:08:15,100 --> 00:08:16,699
Don't worry. I paid the judges in cash.

151
00:08:16,700 --> 00:08:18,200
There's no paper trail.

152
00:08:18,300 --> 00:08:20,399
You bribed the judges?!

153
00:08:20,400 --> 00:08:22,899
Gabrielle, why are we fighting?
We should be celebrating.

154
00:08:22,900 --> 00:08:25,272
I got a limo outside,
a bottle of chilled cristal.

155
00:08:25,273 --> 00:08:27,321
- Come on. Let's go. Let's party.
- Listen to me,

156
00:08:27,322 --> 00:08:28,499
you pimply psychopath,

157
00:08:28,500 --> 00:08:30,399
You and I are never going to "party."

158
00:08:30,400 --> 00:08:31,699
In fact, the only reason

159
00:08:31,700 --> 00:08:33,499
we're ever gonna be
in the same room again

160
00:08:33,500 --> 00:08:36,600
is if you strangle a cheerleader
and I wind up on the jury!

161
00:08:37,700 --> 00:08:39,300
God, I love it when we banter.

162
00:08:47,300 --> 00:08:48,500
Hello, Alma.

163
00:08:50,700 --> 00:08:51,600
Orson.

164
00:08:51,900 --> 00:08:53,799
Uh, I let myself in.
I hope you don't mind.

165
00:08:53,800 --> 00:08:55,200
Not at all.

166
00:08:57,100 --> 00:08:59,199
You seem very cheerful.

167
00:08:59,200 --> 00:09:00,200
Oh, I am,

168
00:09:00,400 --> 00:09:03,200
'Cause the game's over,
and you lost.

169
00:09:03,700 --> 00:09:05,899
I told you what I'd do
if you pushed me away.

170
00:09:05,900 --> 00:09:09,500
Well, I'm afraid that threat
no longer has any teeth in it.

171
00:09:11,200 --> 00:09:14,300
Yes, your mother told me
about Bree's little discovery.

172
00:09:15,400 --> 00:09:17,300
What'd you do with Monique's teeth?

173
00:09:17,400 --> 00:09:20,899
Well, maybe I threw them away.
Maybe I hid them here.

174
00:09:20,900 --> 00:09:21,958
You might find them,

175
00:09:21,959 --> 00:09:23,499
If the police don't find them first.

176
00:09:23,500 --> 00:09:25,899
Oh, I don't think you'll
bring the police into this.

177
00:09:25,900 --> 00:09:27,500
Well, neither will you now.

178
00:09:30,100 --> 00:09:33,800
We're done. Why don't you do us
all a favor and go away?

179
00:09:35,100 --> 00:09:36,699
You shouldn't treat me this way.

180
00:09:36,700 --> 00:09:38,299
Don't bother crying.

181
00:09:38,300 --> 00:09:40,299
Tears might've worked
when we were married,

182
00:09:40,300 --> 00:09:42,499
After you lost the baby.
They won't work now.

183
00:09:42,500 --> 00:09:44,100
We should have kept trying.

184
00:09:45,100 --> 00:09:47,200
If we'd had a child,
we'd still be together.

185
00:09:48,500 --> 00:09:51,600
I know. That's why I stopped trying.

186
00:09:54,200 --> 00:09:55,300
Good-Bye, Alma.

187
00:10:00,500 --> 00:10:03,100
Well, here's some sucky news--

188
00:10:03,800 --> 00:10:05,300
Ken just quit.

189
00:10:05,400 --> 00:10:08,849
- Your new manager? No.
- Yeah,  I'm screwed.

190
00:10:08,850 --> 00:10:10,799
I'm gonna have to drop out
of the street fair.

191
00:10:10,800 --> 00:10:13,799
Tom, no. You can't. You can't.

192
00:10:13,800 --> 00:10:16,099
The pizzeria opens in a week,
and that street fair

193
00:10:16,100 --> 00:10:17,899
is the best advertising
we're gonna get.

194
00:10:17,900 --> 00:10:19,999
I know, but I can't work it alone.

195
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:22,500
Well, you know, hire someone else.

196
00:10:22,600 --> 00:10:24,499
Well, there's no time for that.

197
00:10:24,500 --> 00:10:26,599
The future of the restaurant
is at stake.

198
00:10:26,600 --> 00:10:29,300
It is time to get creative.

199
00:10:29,400 --> 00:10:31,099
Well, I do have one option,

200
00:10:31,100 --> 00:10:34,600
- But it would require some sacrifice.
- Well, whatever it is gonna take.

201
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:36,000
You could help me.

202
00:10:36,900 --> 00:10:37,999
What?! No.

203
00:10:38,608 --> 00:10:39,899
Look, I'm wearing makeup.

204
00:10:39,900 --> 00:10:42,599
I am holding a briefcase.
What does this suggest to you?

205
00:10:42,600 --> 00:10:44,299
You could call in sick.

206
00:10:44,300 --> 00:10:48,799
I can't call in sick
after eight weeks of sick leave,

207
00:10:48,800 --> 00:10:51,000
Especially when I've been fine
for three of them.

208
00:10:51,612 --> 00:10:54,400
Oh! Crap, that's Ed.

209
00:10:55,500 --> 00:10:57,299
Lynette? Lynette, please?

210
00:10:57,300 --> 00:10:59,599
You're the one who said
that we need the street fair.

211
00:10:59,600 --> 00:11:03,965
My boss is waiting for me
outside in his car.

212
00:11:03,966 --> 00:11:05,300
What am I supposed to do?

213
00:11:06,100 --> 00:11:08,700
It's time to get creative.

214
00:11:12,900 --> 00:11:14,900
Oh, there she is.

215
00:11:18,800 --> 00:11:20,200
Hey, guys.

216
00:11:20,500 --> 00:11:23,100
Boy, didn't expect you
to still be wearing a sling.

217
00:11:23,700 --> 00:11:26,199
Yeah, it heals a little slower

218
00:11:26,200 --> 00:11:27,799
when the bullet's still in there.

219
00:11:27,800 --> 00:11:31,200
- Oh. They couldn't get it out?
- No, it's too close.

220
00:11:31,500 --> 00:11:32,400
To what?

221
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:34,799
Everything.

222
00:11:34,800 --> 00:11:36,400
God, I'm so sorry.

223
00:11:38,300 --> 00:11:40,599
Hey, you got a little, uh,
cereal right...

224
00:11:40,600 --> 00:11:42,600
Cereal? I didn't have any, uh...

225
00:11:43,500 --> 00:11:45,100
Oh, I know what that is.

226
00:11:45,500 --> 00:11:47,299
I get nauseous from the pain,

227
00:11:47,300 --> 00:11:49,800
So that's just a little residual vomit.

228
00:11:51,904 --> 00:11:54,099
Lynette, you sure you're ready
to come back to work?

229
00:11:54,100 --> 00:11:56,999
Yeah! Don't be silly. I'm fine.

230
00:11:57,000 --> 00:12:00,199
Come on. Let's go
sell some toothpaste.

231
00:12:00,200 --> 00:12:01,805
All righty! Let's go.

232
00:12:05,512 --> 00:12:07,323
- Son of a bitch!
- Oh! No, no! I'm sorry!

233
00:12:07,324 --> 00:12:09,274
- Don't touch me, okay?
- Anything we can do?

234
00:12:09,275 --> 00:12:11,800
My pills! My pain pills are in my bag.

235
00:12:12,400 --> 00:12:13,600
Thanks.

236
00:12:13,900 --> 00:12:15,799
Oh! Oh, my pills!

237
00:12:15,800 --> 00:12:20,000
I need my pills,
and now they're all dirty!

238
00:12:23,700 --> 00:12:24,999
See ya next week!

239
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:26,900
Thanks for understanding!

240
00:12:32,177 --> 00:12:34,199
Hey. Looks like
an interesting book.

241
00:12:34,200 --> 00:12:35,300
What's it about?

242
00:12:37,121 --> 00:12:38,699
Never mind. I'll wait for the movie.

243
00:12:38,700 --> 00:12:41,900
- What's eating you?
- Those two guys you saved me from?

244
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:43,399
I know you paid 'em to attack me.

245
00:12:43,400 --> 00:12:44,608
That's a lie.

246
00:12:46,372 --> 00:12:48,200
You wanna take a minute
